This paper presents a set of bitext word alignment methods that are especially tailored for language pairs that share traits with Inuktitut-English. Several cross-lingual affinities are exploited by the developed systems: Syllables and substrings are examples of sublexical levels;
consistent transliteration patterns; the innate propensity for alignment monotonicity.
The classifier combination is the foundation of the most effective systems that have been demonstrated. The study also demonstrates that various combination approaches produce the best results based on the target evaluation metrics, including Alignment Error Rate (AER) and F-measure.

By categorising the domain of the document in which a term appears, this paper investigates a number of issues related to determining a term's domain. The authors use Wikipedia and a multilingual thesaurus to present and assess a simple approach for domain classification of documents in 24 languages. Additionally, they look into and offer quantitative findings on:
the degree of consensus among people about the terms' and documents' domain classification;
The probability that terms will inherit their parent document's domain.
